english:
  title: Encomium on the Images of the Sage and the Teacher, with Preface
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Director Sajo, the worthy Hamgun Jajin, gathered artisans to paint images of Zhongni and Yan Hui, and requested that I compose an encomium. Thus I have written the following:

    [On the Sage]

    Teacher of ten thousand generations—
    his virtue transcends all naming.
    As the light of sun and moon shines forth,
    why praise anew what already gleams?
    Yet gazing silently upon his likeness,
    I see the hazy traces of ancient sages.
    He possessed virtue like heaven itself,
    yet the age denied him his proper time.
    Alas, it is thus—
    why was the qilin ever captured?
    Why did the phoenix decline?

    [On the Teacher]

    Kongzi knew the wisdom of Yan the worthy;
    Yan devoted himself to Kong's excellence.
    Saint and sage walk the same Way,
    their hearts joined without separation.
    Though Kong and Yan bear different surnames,
    they were one body with a single purpose.
    As the seventy disciples were,
    so too their forms were many, yet their will was one.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zhongni (仲尼) is a courtesy name of Confucius; Yan Hui is his most celebrated disciple.
  - key: ''
    value: The qilin and phoenix are mythical creatures associated with sage rulers and virtuous times; their absence or decline suggests an age lacking virtue.
  - key: ''
    value: The seventy disciples refers to Confucius's major disciples; the poem suggests that virtue transcends multiplicity of form.
